					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rioghail" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1302192); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1302192&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182998" alt="Rioghail" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1302192)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rioghail" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1302192); return false;" >Rioghail</a></span> <span class="odate time_1532641559 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Jul 2018 21:45</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3886828">
									

<p>I like this one a lot. 'Self-important anartist who talks circles round everyone' is a hard character to execute well, but Veronica lands firm on the side of 'fun' rather than 'tiresome'. I like that she catches Hae flat-footed, since it's a good twist on the standard style of interviews with people who aren't supposed to be in the know. I also like how the difficulty of Veronica's statements is just as much a product of her self-absorption and projection as her secret mystic knowledge - it's a good demonstration of how weird her priorities are.</p>
<p>Probably the only problem I have with this is the Veronica shooting herself at the end of the interview. Given her disdain for Hae, it seems weird that her 'checking up' prompts a desire to kill herself immediately. Plus, it's overly pat and feels like it was written in more as a way to terminate that line of inquiry than as a believable character reaction. It'd be a much less grating development if, say, she kicked Hae out and then was found dead sometime shortly thereafter of an obvious suicide. As it is, it kind of makes her feel like a narrative device rather than a person.</p>
<p>EDIT: Huh, thought Hae was male for some reason (probably 'It's been a pleasure, man').</p>

							</div>

								
